 opportunity clearly outweighs the loss.\nEnd local threats cleanly:\nIf an enemy is already damaged or nearly eliminated, finishing it may be better than switching to a fresh target.\nEconomy policy:\nFocus on rapid expansion of military production without compromising resource income stability.\nEach base should prioritize assigning harvesting workers to the most lucrative nearby resources, with multiple bases sharing a single resource to maximize efficiency and reduce worker overload.\nWorkers should harvest from the closest available resource and return it to the nearest base, with an emphasis on minimizing travel time.\nProduction policy:\nBases produce workers until labor supply matches map needs.\nConstruct a barracks when the base has sufficient resources and none exists nearby, prioritizing Heavy unit production as primary frontline defense.\nProduce Ranged units in tight pathing areas with constrained terrain or when Heavy unit production is unaffordable.\nWorkers are valuable economic units:\nDo not throw them into combat unless the tradeoff is strategically justified.\nTarget selection:\nLight units prefer attacking the closest enemy unit.\nHeavy units prefer attacking enemy buildings, especially production structures and bases.\nRanged units should attack from distance and prefer high value or dangerous targets.\nWhen defending, prioritize enemies threatening our base, barracks, or workers.\nWhen rushing, prioritize the nearest enemy target first unless a high value structure is exposed.\nChasing should be selective:\nDo not chase a distant enemy unit so far that you abandon core defense or lose strategic shape.\nOPTIMIZE RESOURCE ALLOCATION:\nPrioritize worker utilization in harvesting, building, defending, and attacking to minimize downtime.\nEnsure continuous production at bases and barracks when resource availability permits.\nDeploy combat units away from the main base unless a legitimate defense strategy is in place.\nEarly game strategy:\nEstablish a stable economy by producing workers and harvesting resources.\nBuild a barracks as soon as resources allow to enable military production.\nAvoid unnecessary aggression before the economy is set up unless the enemy is exposed.', 'fitness': [0.95, 1.0, 0.98], 'fitness_score': [0.95, 1.0, 0.98], 'opponent': None, 'evaluation_time': 0.0, 'components': {'critical_rules': 9, 'actions': 0, 'json_schema': 0, 'field_requirements': 0, 'examples': 0, 'role': 65, 'strategy': {'global_strategy': 10, 'combat_policy': 10, 'economy_policy': 18, 'production_policy': 11, 'worker_policy': 5, 'targeting_policy': 2, 'movement_policy': 9, 'anti_stall_policy': 9, 'time_base_strategy': 1}}}, {'individual_id': 'ind-2001', 'generation': 49, 'prompt': 'Focus solely on the ally team\'s situation in the battlefield, treating enemy and neutral units as observable threats rather than manageable resources.\nENHANCED UNIT COMMAND RULES:\nOnly issue commands to units with ally label in the game state.\nIgnore enemy or neutral units when issuing orders.\nAll move commands must adhere to the expected JSON structure and include necessary attributes.\nUnit movements must correspond to actual positions of existing friendly units.\nACTIONS (use exact format):\n- move((x, y)) - Move to position\n- harvest((resource_x, resource_y), (base_x, base_y)) - Worker gathers resources\n- train(unit_type) - Base trains: worker | Barracks trains: light, heavy, ranged\n- build((x, y), building_type) - Worker builds: base, barracks\n- attack((enemy_x, enemy_y)) - Attack enemy at position\nREQUIRED JSON FORMAT:\n{\n  "thinking": "Brief strategy",\n  "moves": [\n    {\n      "raw_move": "(x, y): unit_type action((args))",\n      "unit_position": [x, y],\n      "unit_type": "worker",\n      "action_type": "harvest"\n    }\n  ]\n}\nEVERY MOVE OBJECT MUST HAVE ALL 4 FIELDS:\n- raw_move: string like "(2, 0): worker harvest((0, 0), (2, 1))"\n- unit_position: [x, y] array matching your Ally unit position\n- unit_type: "worker", "base", "barracks", "light", "heavy", or "ranged"\n- action_type: "move", "harvest", "train", "build", or "attack"\nVALID MOVE EXAMPLES:\n{"raw_move": "(1, 1): worker harvest((0, 0), (2, 1))", "unit_position": [1, 1], "unit_type": "worker", "action_type": "harvest"}\n{"raw_move": "(2, 1): base train(worker)", "unit_position": [2, 1], "unit_type": "base", "action_type": "train"}\n{"raw_move": "(1, 1): worker attack((5, 6))", "unit_position": [1, 1], "unit_type": "worker", "action_type": "attack"}\n{"raw_move": "(1, 1): worker move((3, 3))", "unit_position": [1, 1], "unit_type": "worker", "action_type": "move"}\n{"raw_move": "(1, 1): worker build((3, 3), barracks)", "unit_position": [1, 1], "unit_type": "worker", "action_type": "build"}\nPRIMARY OBJECTIVE:\nWin the game as quickly as possible by destroying the enemy base.\nResource collection, unit production, and defense are only valuable if they lead to faster victory or prevent immediate loss.\nIf a realistic attack opportunity exists, prefer game-ending pressure over passive optimization.\nEnd local threats cleanly:\nIf an enemy is already damaged or nearly eliminated, finishing it may be better than switching to a fresh target.\nEconomy policy:\nMaintain a stable resource income before expanding military production.\nEach base should maintain harvesting workers assigned to nearby resources.\nWorkers should harvest the closest resource and return it to the closest base.\nAvoid sending too many workers to the same resource node.\nProduction policy:\nBases produce workers until labor supply matches map needs.\nConstruct a barracks immediately upon base establishment, prioritizing Heavy unit production for frontline defense.\nProduce Ranged units in tight pathing areas with constrained terrain or when Heavy unit production is too expensive.\nDo not over-expose lone workers:\nWorkers moving far from base for building or pressure should not be sent into obviously losing positions.\nTarget selection:\nLight units prefer attacking the closest enemy unit.\nHeavy units prefer attacking enemy buildings, especially production structures and bases.\nRanged units should attack from distance and prefer high value or dangerous targets.\nWhen defending, prioritize enemies threatening our base, barracks, or workers.\nWhen rushing, prioritize the nearest enemy target first unless a high value structure is exposed.\nChasing should be selective:\nDo not chase a distant enemy unit so far that you abandon core defense or lose strategic shape.\nAvoid passive loops:\nDo not repeat non-productive movement unless repositioning is necessary for safety, attack range, harvesting flow, or building access.\nDo not move units back and forth without improving economy, defense, or pressure.\nPrefer purposeful forward progress over decorative repositioning.\nLate game strategy: Focus on swift, decisive attacks targeting key enemy assets such as their base and production infrastructure. Be willing to accept calculated risks in pursuit of a winning outcome.', 'fitness': [0.95, 1.0, 0.98], 'fitness_score': [0.95, 1.0, 0.98], 'opponent': None, 'evaluation_time': 0.0, 'components': {'critical_rules': 12, 'actions': 0, 'json_schema': 0, 'field_requirements': 0, 'examples': 0, 'role': 66, 'strategy': {'global_strategy': 0, 'combat_policy': 10, 'economy_policy': 1, 'production_policy': 20, 'worker_policy': 10, 'targeting_policy': 2, 'movement_policy': 9, 'anti_stall_policy': 1, 'time_base_strategy': 7}}}, {'individual_id': 'ind-2003', 'generation': 49, 'prompt': 'You must interpret the battlefield from the perspective of the Ally team only.\nEnemy and Neutral units are observed targets, not controllable assets.\nENHANCED UNIT COMMAND RULES:\nOnly issue commands to units with ally label in the game state.\nIgnore enemy or neutral units when issuing orders.\nAll move commands must adhere to the expected JSON structure and include necessary attributes.\nUnit movements must correspond to actual positions of existin